{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/0034058093A/1958032801/0274.xml":{"full_text":"Ballot on Major Issues\nMay Be Postponed\nUntil Mld'April\nt\n((MM fNua 9am <M\nEtoenhower desired to wait, Know\nland indicated, to see the scope of\nre-employment resulting from step-\nped-up defense expenditures end\nwhatever public works are put into\nmotion. The new timetable, if the\nAdministration is able to make it\nstick, would postpone until the middle\nof May four and a half months\nafter Congress entered its new ses\nsion\u2014a solid commitment on taxes.\nThe housing bill sent to the White\nHouse by House concurrence in a\nSenate-originated measure would pro\nvide $1.9 billion in loan guarantees\nand other steps to stimulate construc\ntion and provide jobs. Sponsored by\nSenator John J. Sparkman (D-Ala.),\nthe Mil went through only after Re\npublicans had forced through a provi\nsion raising interest rates on veterans\u2019\nhousing from 4% to 4% per cent\nVice President Nixon -cast a tic\nbreaking vote to copper-rivet this\nlanguage in the bill after a democratic\namendment had failed to remove It.\nVotes were all but unanimous in\nboth the House and Senate asking the\nAdministration to speed expenditures\nfor military and civilian construction\nalready appropriated for. The resolu\ntions, however, have no force of law,\nand Republicans were able to water\ndown their impact by getting accept\nance of an addition \"commending\u201d\nthe Administration for stepped-up\nspending it had already approved.\nA Senate Public Works sub-commit\ntee voted approval of a bill to spend\nan additional $1.5 billion this year on\nthe federal interstate highway system.\nDespite direct opposition by President\nElsenhower ~to the measure as \u201ctoo\nbig,\u201d Senate flow action was sched\nuled before Easter recess. The bill was\ntemporarily delayed by a dispute over\nanti-billboard provisions.\nThe Senate passed a bill to \"cor\nrect\u201d existing law on life Insurance\ncompany earnings by reducing the tax\nthe companies must pay on 1957 in\ncome by $124 million. It defeated as\n\"premature\u201d amendments by Senator\nPaul H. Douglas (D-Dl.) to reduce in\ncome and excise taxes and by Senator\nRalph W. Yarborough (D Tex.) to\nraise personal tax exemptions from\n$600 to $800.\nSenator J. William Fulbright (D\nArk.), chairman of the Banking and\nCurrency Committee, introduced a\nmeasure to authorize $2 billion in\nfederal long-term loans to states and\ncities for local public works. Senator\nStyles Bridges (R-N. H.) called for\nrevival of a large-scale Reconstruc\ntion Finance Corp. to lend federal\nmoney to business enterprises, such as\nrailroads, that face trouble.\nIn this flurry of activity,, political\njockeying between the two parties\ncontinued. Fulbright took the Senate\nfloor to complain that Eisenhower\nin a letter tried to create an impres\nsion that he was \"pressing\u201d Congress\nand that Congress, in turn was show\ning \u201creluctance to act\u201d on aati-recea\nsian measures.\nNothing of the sort, said Fulbright.\nThe Administration request* were\neither \u201croutine,\u201d \"meaningless\u201d or\nstymied by the Administration\u2019s own\nshortsightedness and delay.\nThe President\u2019s upcoming program\nfor federal assistance to supplement\nflie exhausted unemployment compen\nsation of growing thousands of work\ners was delayed by an Internal quar\nrel over whether money should be ad\nvanced as loans or outright grants.\nA powerful lobby of state employ\nment security officials\u2014state bureau\ncrats whose local \u201cempires\u201d would be\ndamaged by federal \"intrusion\" in\ntheir programs\u2014fought hard against\ngrants. Eisenhower called In the ex\necutive committee of the Governors\u2019\nConference before reaching a decision\non a detailed program already delay\ned for two weeks after Its announce\nment in principle.\nThe Issue of tax reduction was bot\ntled up, for all practical purposes,\nwhen a \"gentlemen\u2019s agreement\u201d was\nreached between House Democrats\nand the Administration that neither\nwould \"Jump the gun\u201d by offering Its\nown tax-relief program without ad\nvance notice to toe other on timing.\nThe \"gentlemen\u2019s poet, It wao un\nderstood, applied only to riming and\nnot to the content of any program\n1 finally offered. Democrats ts the\nHouse, which under the constitution\nmust originate all revenue measures\ntnohidlag tax cuts, tended to ridicule\n.c'tto Administration's desire to delay\nn decision a month longer than previ\n.But Democrats themselves had not\nyst reached a formal agreement on\n|bs kind of measure they would fin\nally sponsor and seek to drive\nthrough, pt\u2014My against massive\nWhite House opposition, when Om\nits vacation and\nthe April 10 figures are published on\nMarch employment and Joblessness.\nVice Jresident Nixon and Labor\nSecretary James P. Mitchell, two Ad\nministrative spokesmen who have\nspoken in favor of early tax cuts, also\ncommitted themselves to \"across-the\nboard\u201d relief. Ibis phrase, generally\nmeans cuts to favor corporations and\nhigh-level tax-payers rather than em\nphasize increased purchasing power\nby concentrating tax reduction among\nlow-income families.\nMitchell\n(Oenttaaed frees Page One)\npossible, even greater dispatch than In\nnormal times, and that employment\nservices be fully maintained to the\nend that unemployed workers get\nback on the job as promptly as pos\nsible.\u201d\nFailure of the Administration thus\nfar to Induce the states to enact ade\nquate unemployment compensation\nhas led organized labor to reiterate\nits demands for improved federal\nstandards. The Kennedy-Mc Oarthy\nbill, before Congress, which calls for\nfederal standards, is strongly sup\nported by the AFL-CXO.\nVA Announces\nPilot Study for\nVet Claims\nWilliam Holsinger, Cleveland Man\nager for the Veterans Administration\nthis week announced a new pilot\nstudy now is underway to review vet\nerans\u2019 claims that were disallowed\nafter World War n.\nSumner G. Whittier, Administra\ntor of Veterans Affairs, informed him\nthe pilot study is the converse of the\ncurrent review of compensation and\npension claims that were allowed over\nthe name period.\nMr. Holsinger learned the pilot\nstudy Is now being conducted in the\nVA regional offices at Brooklyn,\nN. V.; Milwaukee, Wis.; Togus, Me.;\nWichita, Kane.; Seattle, Wash.;\nColumbia, S. C., and Lubback, Tex.\nThrough this study, VA will come up\nwith one of three conclusions:\n1\u2014 A review of disallowed claims\nwould not be worth the effort; or,\n2\u2014 A further extension of the pilot\nstudy would be in order; or,\nS\u2014A full-scale nation-wide review\nof disallowed claims is necessary.\nMr. Whittier has ordered the pilot\nstudy at the request of veterans\u2019 or\nganizations which believe VA may\nhave erred in disallowing some of the\nclaims. Holsinger stated that although\nCleveland\u2019s VA Office is not in the\npilot study, in the event that a basis\nis found to review all disallowed\nclaims, he will then initiate action\nfor a reevaluation of all of that type\nclaim In the Cleveland Jurisdiction.\nRUBBER WORKERS SEE ,\u00a7tt\u00a3\nCONGRESS IN ACTION MB\nto -Investigate malpractices in tbs\nUnited States. TYue or false,\u201d one\nquestion on the quis read.\nProbably because headlines are on\ncongressional committee investiga\ntions now, a number thought that was\ntrue. False, is correct, and the stu\ndents learned that the primary duty of\nCongress is to enact the laws, and\nthat investigations are only a part of\nthe process in determining what new\nlaws, if any, might be proposed.\nHarry Conn, editor of Press Asso\nciates, labor press news service, told\nthe students a little more about that\nin a Sunday dinner talk.\n\u201cThe McClellan Committee is some\nthing different now,\u201d he said. \u201cIt was\nset up to investigate corrupt practices\nin management and labor. But now,\nit is delving Into a labor dispute be\ntween the United Auto Workers and\nthe Kohler Co. and even the Jhostile\nSenators admit there Is no corrup\ntion hi tide.\u201d\nIn a Monday morning breakfast\nsession, Hyman Bookbinder, AFL-cio\nlegislative representative, said, \"Our\nobject as legislative representatives is\nnot to get a Democratic or Repub\nlican victory, but to get a victory on\nan issue that is good for the people.\"\n\u201cTour letter to your congressman\nis what counts and can do more than\nall the legislative representatives put\ntogether,\" he added. \u201cA letter carries\na lot of weight with a congressman.\u201d\nThe students toured the Capitol\nbuilding Monday, sat in on the morn\ning session of the McClellan Commit\ntee hearings and then filed into the\nsolemn chambers of the U. S. Supreme\nCourt tor the noon session of that\ncourt.\nIn the afternoon, some attended\nHouse and Senate sessions. Others\nvisited their congressmen or tried to\nmake appointments for later hi the\nweek.\nRep. lee Metcalf, Montana Demo\ncrat, was tiie Monday dinner speaker.\nHe said a three-pronged program of\nschool construction, scholarships and\nteacher salary increases, all financed\nby a Federal aid to education pro\ngram, would help turn the tide of\nthe recession and raise educational\nstandards.\nEverett Ksssalow, AFL-CIO Indus\ntrial Union Department research di\nrector, told the students at a Tues\nday breakfast session the quickest\nway to brake the recession and to get\nthe economy climbing again is to cut\nincome taxes now. An increase in the\npersonal exemption from the present\n$600 to $800 would be like a pay in\ncrease of 10 cents an hour and that\nmoney would be spent and would put\nworkers back on the Job, he said.\nSenator William Proxmire, Wiscon\nsin Democrat, called for immediate\naction on boosting unemployment\ncompensation benefits and increasing\nsocial security payments when he\nspoke at the Tuesday noon session in\nthe Capitol building dining room. He\nsaid this money would boost purchas\ning' power and help stem tits recession\ntide.\nSenator Ralph Yarborough, Taxes\nDemocrat, wad the Tuesday dinner\nspeaker. He said the recent chargee\nof influence peddling to the Federal\nOommunlcattana Commission to con-\nnection with the granting of a m\u00ab\u00abi\ntelevision station license points up the\nneed far strengthening the laws to\nmake Federal regulatory agencies car-\nnpUoibfnofc\nArthur Goldberg, AFTr-CTO general\ncounsel, told students at a Wednes\nday breakfast session that hostile\nsenators to the McClellan Committee\nwould like to write a law that would\noutlaw companywide and industry*\nwide bargaining.\n\u201cI don\u2019t think theyTJ succeed, be*\ncause I think a sense of equity among\nthe right-thinking American people\nwill prevail,\u201d he said.\nDean Ashesou, Secretary of State\nunder former President Truman, talk\ned off-the-cuff on foreign policy at\na Wednesday luncheon session with\nthe unionists. He sold a strong United\nStates nuclear force to Europe might\nmake Russia back down on any plans\nfor over-running Western Europe. He\ncalled for the United States to give\nleadership to the free world to re\ngain prestige that has slipped away\nbecause of administration policies.\nRep. Frank Thompson, Jr., New\nJersey Democrat, at a Wednesday\ndinner, said citizens have the abso\nlute right to demand of the Repre\nsentatives they send to Congress to\nsee that the Federal Government as\nsumes its responsibilities in educa\ntion, homing, and general welfare.\nGeneral Secretary-Treasurer Des\nmond Walker conducted the Thursday\nsession, covering the necessity for\nCommittee on Political Education\nfund raising and bow to put into ac\ntion what was learned during the in\nstitute. V|.\nAmong the students were E. E.\nMcHenry, Art Mtoson, H. E. Gallo\nway, James K. Sherrill, William Cart\nright, Howard Hildebrand, Dan\nCampano, Mrs. .Mary Lena House,\nMrs. Ann Oartright and Mrs. Theila\nChilds, all of Akron; Harold O. Boyce\nand Addison R. Patton of Mansfield,\nOhio; Joe Sauter of Denver; Henry\nE. Jones of Dayton, Ohio; James E.\nCook, Donald J. Oonty, Andrew Ugro\nvitch, Joseph DeLuca, Joseph Vasi\nlenko and Daniel McClerry of Passaic,\nN. J.; Frances Laferrlere and Mary\nConnor of Woonsocket, R. I.{ Frank\nW. Randolph, James E. Brown and\nLouis Abtogton of New Haven, Conn.;\nFrancis Zabioki, Peter Kozak and\nAugustine Ctobattonl of Oaks, Pa.\nThey came, they saw, they learned\nand now thsyte teaching the\nworker at the next machine or the\nperson to the seat next to them on the\nbus. i\nanviMuiM* Mm rtraucATioN\n\u2022instoi ram\nHUNTING\nAkron, Ohio\nDANNI*~PM*IDINT\nDoes such wonderful things for us. Take frying. You can set the.\nflame at the exact heat, with the new Burner-with-a-Brain. The\nheat's never so low that we soak up grease... never too high\nso we don't cook through. With controllable gas cooking, we fry\ngolden-tender moist and delicious right to the bone.\n\u2022v ,r\nv-:\n*mt\ncr. i\ns' L\n\u201c\u2022V;\n\nTIE CUT III! US H CIMMRT\nk\n-.W- i.i I. A^V.-' *1\ni.V K\nr v\nj\n.j, .H y w.* \u2018xi^-,-v**\u25a0: i\u00bb'V\n5f*V-^\u00ab.\n\nV f\n\u201cAction Now,\u201dl\nIs Requested\nBy Labor W\ncontinued in February. Industrial yn<\nAuction, employment inocmes, and 1\nretell sales again declined and narn\nployment rose to a new psstum\nUgh.\"\n2\u2014The CMnmeree Dept, reported\na $2 billion drop In personal income in\nFebruary as compared to Jamiljr and\na to .8 billion decrease dram a year\nago.\nWages and salaries exceeded.the\ngeneral drop, falling o\u00ab $2.4 billion\nfrom the aJnuary rate and |6-8 bil\nlion from February 1957.\n8\u2014The Labor Dept, reported that\nnear claims for unemployment bam\nonce, a rough measure of new layoffs,\nrose to 447,414 in the first week of\"\nMarch\u2014a week that normally shows a\ndecline in claims.\nIn file last week of February file\nnumber of workers collecting jobless\nbenefits rose to 3,358,308 compered to\n1,756,070 a year ago.\n4\u2014 The Commerce Dept; reported\nthat business plans to spend |5 U\nUon, or 18 per cent, less for near plant\nand equipment In 1958 than last year.\nExcept for pubUe utilities aQ major\nindustries expect to reduce their out\nlays daring the year. The IS per cent\ndrop would be the font since 1949.\n5\u2014 The Federal Deserve Board,\nwith the eld of toe Univ. of Michi\ngan\u2019s Survey Research Center, re\nported that consomen were concerned\nabout the general business outlook\nand viewed their *l-*~*l~l positions\nand prospects leas favorably than n\nyea* ago.\nThe sampling of consumer confi\ndence showed fewer families planning\nto buy durable goods end that pros\npects for new car sales were the low\nest since 1951. I\n8\u2014Rail Retirement Board reported\nthat the number of jobless railroad\nworkers doubled since a year ago with\n11 per cent unemployed in February\nand Increasing In March.\nRobert c. Goodwin, director of the\nlabor Dept.\u2019s Bureau of Employment\nSecurity, told a House Labor Sub\ncommittee that the number of persons\nexhausting unemployment benefits Is\nrising and can be expeoted to move\nupward sharply in April and May.\nBishms Register\nCompfield Hickman\nFuneral Horn*\nFUNERAL DIRECTORS\n24 Hour Arpbulance Service\nOxygen Equipped\nSee Perk Are., W. SH 5-1161\nBARBERTON. OHIO\n5-30\nFred Arbogost tr Co., Inc.\nMaker* of\nJITTER BUG HAWAIIAN WIGGIER\nHULA POPPER\n311 Wee* Nertk Street BL1-2177\nAKRON 4, OHIO\n6-6\nEeet Akron Ineurance Agency\nGENERAL INSURANCE\nE. A. Wagner, Manager\n915 L Market Sheer PO 2-7615\nAKRON, OHIO\n6-6\nDemand This Lahti on\nYour Printing.\nAkron Allied Printing\nTrades Council\nBOX 127 AKRON 9, OHIO\n4-n\nOriginal Barbecue Made\nRIB STEAK AND CHICKEN DINNERS\n52 Beit Murker Sheet BL 1-0197\nAKROHOMIO\n5-30\nNorman C Whitley, M.T.\nArthritis Lumbago Nervousness\nConstipation Paralysis Insomnia, Etc.\nMASSAGE and CABINET BATHS\nMake An Appointment Today.\n1910-11th Sheet S